# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: color-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In 1931, the International Commission on Illumination (CIE) published the **CIE 1931 color spaces** which define the relationship between the visible spectrum and human color vision.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE color spaces are mathematical models that comprise a "standard observer", which is a static idealization of the color vision of a normal human.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] A useful application of the CIEXYZ colorspace is that a mixture of two colors in some proportion lies on the straight line between those two colors.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] One disadvantage is that it is not perceptually uniform.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] This disadvantage is remedied in subsequent color models such as CIELUV and CIELAB, but these and modern color models still use the CIE 1931 color spaces as a foundation.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE developed and maintains many of the standards in use today relating to colorimetry.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE color spaces were created using data from a series of experiments, where human test subjects adjusted red, green, and blue primary colors to find a visual match to a second, pure color.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The original experiments were conducted in the mid-1920s by William David Wright using ten observers and John Guild using seven observers.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The experimental results were combined, creating the CIE RGB color space.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE XYZ color space was derived from CIE RGB in an effort to simplify the math.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These color spaces are fundamental tools for measuring color for industry, including inks, dyes, and paints, illumination, color imaging, etc.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE color spaces contributed to the development of color television, the creation of instruments for maintaining consistent color in manufacturing processes, and other methods of color management.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Normal human color vision is trichromatic, which is enabled by three classes of cone cells (L, M & S).
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Each cone class contains a slightly different photopsin with a different spectral sensitivity.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The spectral sensitivities are summarized by their peak wavelengths, which are at long ("L", 560 nm), medium ("M", 530 nm), and short ("S", 420 nm) wavelengths, sometimes shorthanded inexactly as red, green and blue cones, respectively.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The differential excitation levels of these three cones comprise the tristimulus values, denoted "L", "M", and "S", and are the parameters that define the 3-dimensional "LMS color space", which is one of many color spaces devised to quantify human color vision.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In principle, any human color sensation can be described by a set of tristimulus values.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These are all inner products and can be thought of as a projection of an infinite-dimensional spectrum to a three-dimensional color.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] This LMS color model is refined to the LMS color space when the spectral sensitivity "primaries" are defined according to the standard observer.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The LMS color space can be further transformed into similar three-dimensional color spaces, such as RGB, XYZ, HSV or cognates thereof.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The tristimulus values associated with a color space can be conceptualized as amounts of three primary colors in a trichromatic, additive color model.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In some color spaces, including the LMS and XYZ spaces, the primary colors used are not real colors in the sense that they cannot be generated in any spectral power distribution of light.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Since a lot of information is lost during the conversion (projection) of a continuous light spectrum to tristimulus values, it follows that there are disparate spectra that can stimulate the same tristimulus values.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These disparate spectra are known as **metamers**.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For example, a monochromatic 570 nm (yellow) light is *metameric* with a dichromatic light spectrum comprising 2 parts monochromatic 535 nm (green) light and 1 part monochromatic 700 nm (red) light (accounting for luminosity).
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In 1853, Hermann Grassmann developed Grassmann's laws, which aimed to describe color mixing algebraically.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These laws laid the theoretical framework necessary for color experiments performed by Hermann von Helmholtz (remembered for popularizing the trichromatic theory) and James Clerk Maxwell in the 1850's, and later in the experiments used to develop the CIE 1931 color spaces.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These laws assume that human color vision is linear, which is approximately true.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE 1931 color spaces are 4 interrelated color spaces with the same origin.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In the 1920s, two independent experiments on human color perception were conducted by W.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] David Wright with ten observers, and John Guild with seven observers.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] How their results laid the foundation of the CIE 1931 color spaces is described in this section.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These experiments sought to quantify the typical human chromatic response (color perception) and define it as the **standard (colorimetric) observer**.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The standard observer is defined by the 3 color matching functions in one of the CIE 1931 color spaces.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The Wright–Guild color matching experiments were conducted using a circular color screen split into equal semicircles (a bipartite field).
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The screen was positioned at a distance from the subject (observer) such that its diameter subtended 2° of the subject's vision.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In one half of the screen, a test (target) color was projected, while on the other half an observer-adjustable color was projected.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The adjustable color was a mixture of three monochromatic primary colors, each with adjustable brightness.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The subject would alter the brightness of each of the three primary beams until the halves appeared metameric.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These are the RGB color-matching functions.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Any spectral distribution can be thought of as a combination of a number of monochromatic sources at varying intensities, so that (by Grassmann's laws) integrating the color-matching functions with that spectral distribution will yield the intensities of the three primaries necessary to match it.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The problem is that the three primaries can only produce colors which lie within their gamut – the triangle in color space formed by the primaries, which never touches the monochromatic locus nor the purple line except at the three primaries.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In other words, there is no monochromatic target that can be matched by a combination of the three primaries, except at the wavelengths of the three primaries themselves.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Matching a monochromatic target would require one of the primaries to have a negative brightness.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] While this is physically impossible, it can be approximated (relying on Grassmann's laws) by adding the negative primary to the target field instead of subtracting it from the adjustment field, thereby allowing a match to be made with negative primary brightness.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For wavelengths between the blue and green primaries, some red primary must be added to the target, resulting in negative values of ${\bar {r}}(\lambda )$ .
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Likewise, between the green and red primaries, some blue must be added to the target, resulting in negative values of ${\bar {b}}(\lambda )$ .
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For wavelengths below the wavelength of the blue primary, or above the wavelength of the red primary, some green must be added and ${\bar {g}}(\lambda )$ will be negative.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For every spectral color, except those defined by the primary colors, there will always be two positive color-matching functions and one negative (as long as the primaries are all monochromatic).
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE RGB color space is one of many RGB color spaces, each distinguished by their particular set of primary colors.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The primaries with wavelengths 546.1 nm and 435.8 nm were chosen because they are easily reproducible monochromatic lines of a mercury vapor discharge.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The 700 nm wavelength, which in 1931 was difficult to reproduce as a monochromatic beam, was chosen because the eye's perception of color is rather unchanging at this wavelength, and therefore small errors in wavelength of this primary would have little effect on the results.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The (un-normalized) color matching functions are the amounts of primaries needed to match the monochromatic target color.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These functions are shown in the plot on the right.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The color matching functions and primaries were settled upon by a CIE special commission after considerable deliberation.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The cut-offs at the short- and long-wavelength side of the diagram are chosen somewhat arbitrarily; the human eye can actually see light with wavelengths up to about 810 nm, but with a sensitivity that is many thousand times lower than for green light.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These color matching functions define what is known as the "1931 CIE standard observer".
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Rather than specify the brightness of each primary, the curves are normalized to have constant area beneath them.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The resulting normalized color matching functions are then scaled in the r:g:b ratio of 1:4.5907:0.0601 for source luminance and 72.0962:1.3791:1 for source radiance to reproduce the true color matching functions.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] By proposing that the primaries be standardized, the CIE established an international system of objective color notation.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] After the definition of the RGB model of human vision using the CIE RGB matching functions, the CIE special commission wished to derive another color space from the CIE RGB color space.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] It was assumed that Grassmann's law held, and the new space would be related to the CIE RGB space by a linear transformation.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The ${\overline {y}}(\lambda )$ color matching function would be exactly equal to the photopic luminous efficiency function *V*(*λ*) for the "CIE standard photopic observer".
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The luminance function describes the variation of perceived brightness with wavelength.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The fact that the luminance function could be constructed by a linear combination of the RGB color matching functions was not guaranteed by any means but might be expected to be nearly true due to the near-linear nature of human sight.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Again, the main reason for this requirement was computational simplification.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For the constant energy white point, it was required that *x* = *y* = *z* = 1/3.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] By virtue of the definition of chromaticity and the requirement of positive values of *x* and *y*, it can be seen that the gamut of all colors will lie inside the triangle [1, 0], [0, 0], [0, 1].
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] It was required that the gamut fill this space practically completely.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] It was found that the ${\overline {z}}(\lambda )$ color matching function could be set to zero above 650 nm while remaining within the bounds of experimental error.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For computational simplicity, it was specified that this would be so.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The derived CIE XYZ color space encompasses all color sensations that are perceptible to a typical human.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The underlying color matching functions can be thought of as the spectral sensitivity curves of three linear light detectors yielding the CIE tristimulus values *X*, *Y* and *Z*.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Collectively, these three functions describe the CIE standard observer.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] That is why CIE XYZ tristimulus values are a device-invariant representation of color.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] It serves as a standard reference against which many other color spaces are defined.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] A set of color-matching functions, like the spectral sensitivity curves of the LMS color space, but not restricted to non-negative sensitivities, associates physically produced light spectra with specific tristimulus values.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Most wavelengths stimulate two or all three kinds of cone cell because the spectral sensitivity curves of the three kinds overlap.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Certain tristimulus values are thus physically impossible: e.g.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] LMS tristimulus values that are non-zero for the M component and zero for both the L and S components.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Furthermore pure spectral colors would, in any normal trichromatic additive color space, e.g., the RGB color spaces, imply negative values for at least one of the three primaries because the chromaticity would be outside the color triangle defined by the primary colors.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] To avoid these negative RGB values, and to have one component that describes the perceived brightness, "imaginary" primary colors and corresponding color-matching functions were formulated.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE 1931 color space defines the resulting tristimulus values, in which they are denoted by "X", "Y", and "Z".
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In the CIE 1931 model, *Y* is the luminance, *Z* is quasi-equal to blue (of CIE RGB), and *X* is a mix of the three CIE RGB curves chosen to be nonnegative.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Setting *Y* as luminance has the useful result that for any given *Y* value, the XZ plane will contain all possible chromaticities at that luminance.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The unit of the tristimulus values *X*, *Y*, and *Z* is often arbitrarily chosen so that *Y* = 1 or *Y* = 100 is the brightest white that a color display supports.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In this case, the Y value is known as the relative luminance.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The corresponding whitepoint values for *X* and *Z* can then be inferred using the standard illuminants.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Since the XYZ values are defined much earlier than the characterization of cone cells in the 1950s (by Ragnar Granit), the physiological meaning of these values were known only much later.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The Hunt-Pointer-Estevez matrix from the 1980s relates XYZ with LMS.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In other words, the Z value is solely made up of the S cone response, the Y value a mix of L and M responses, and X value a mix of all three.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] This fact makes XYZ values analogous to, but different from, the LMS cone responses of the human eye.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In geometrical terms, choosing the new color space amounts to choosing a new triangle in *rg* chromaticity space.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In the figure above-right, the *rg* chromaticity coordinates are shown on the two axes in black, along with the gamut of the 1931 standard observer.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Shown in red are the CIE *xy* chromaticity axes which were determined by the above requirements.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The requirement that the XYZ coordinates be non-negative means that the triangle formed by Cr, Cg, Cb must encompass the entire gamut of the standard observer.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The line connecting Cr and Cb is fixed by the requirement that the ${\overline {y}}(\lambda )$ function be equal to the luminance function.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] This line is the line of zero luminance, and is called the alychne.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The requirement that the ${\overline {z}}(\lambda )$ function be zero above 650 nm means that the line connecting Cg and Cr must be tangent to the gamut in the region of Kr.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The above described transformation is a linear transformation from the CIE RGB space to XYZ space.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The numbers in the conversion matrix below are exact, with the number of digits specified in CIE standards.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The above matrix is balanced for the equi-energy stimulus: it has coordinates (1,1,1) in both RGB and XYZ coordinates.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] While the above matrix is exactly specified in standards, the inverse is left unspecified so that it can be approximated to machine precision to reduce round-trip rounding errors.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The XYZ primaries will have XYZ coordinates [1,0,0], [0,1,0], and [0,0,1] in XYZ space, so the columns of the inverse matrix above specify the XYZ primaries ( Cr, Cg and Cb) in RGB space.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The r and g coordinates of the XYZ primaries are indicated in the rg chromaticity space diagram above.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The integrals of the XYZ color matching functions must all be equal by requirement 3 above, and this is set by the integral of the photopic luminous efficiency function by requirement 2 above.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The tabulated sensitivity curves have a certain amount of arbitrariness in them.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The shapes of the individual *X*, *Y* and *Z* sensitivity curves can be measured with a reasonable accuracy.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] However, the overall luminosity curve (which in fact is a weighted sum of these three curves) is subjective, since it involves asking a test person whether two light sources have the same brightness, even if they are in completely different colors.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Along the same lines, the relative magnitudes of the *X*, *Y*, and *Z* curves are arbitrary.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Furthermore, one could define a valid color space with an *X* sensitivity curve that has twice the amplitude.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] This new color space would have a different shape.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The sensitivity curves in the CIE 1931 and 1964 XYZ color spaces are scaled to have equal areas under the curves.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Three dimensional color can be divided into two parts: brightness and chromaticity.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For example, the color white is a bright color, while the color grey is considered to be a less bright version of that same white.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In other words, the chromaticity of white and grey are the same while their brightness differs.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE xyY color space was deliberately designed so that the *Y* parameter is also a measure of the luminance of a color.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] That is, because each tristimulus parameter, *X*, *Y*, *Z*, is divided by the sum of all three, the resulting values, *x*, *y*, *z*, each represent a proportion of the whole and so their sum must be equal to one.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Therefore, the value *z* can be deduced by knowing *x* and *y*, and consequently the latter two values are sufficient for describing the chromaticity of any color.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The derived color space specified by *x*, *y*, and *Y* is known as the CIE xyY color space and is widely used to specify colors in practice.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Mathematically the colors of the chromaticity diagram occupy a region of the real projective plane.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The figures on the right show the related chromaticity diagram.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The outer curved boundary is the *spectral locus*, with wavelengths shown in nanometers.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The chromaticity diagram is a tool to specify the quality of a color regardless of its brightness.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For examples, grey has the same chromaticity as white, and teal has the same chromaticity as cyan, because the only difference between them is their brightness, not their spectral purity.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These formulas can be derived from the definitions of the x and y chromaticity coordinates by taking advantage of the fact that XYZ (tristimulus) values are additive.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] In place of the luminance values L1, L2, etc., one can use any photometric quantity proportional to the tristimulus value Y (including, of course, Y itself) in the context of interest; this also applies to the following mixing ratio computation.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] As previously stated, when two colors are mixed, the resulting color xmix, ymix lies on the straight line segment that connects them on the CIE xy chromaticity diagram.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] where L1 is the luminance of color x1, y1 and L2 the luminance of color x2, y2.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Because ymix is unambiguously determined by xmix and vice versa (unless x1 = x2 or y1 = y2), one is enough to compute the mixing ratio.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] where $\lambda$ is the wavelength of the equivalent monochromatic light (measured in nanometers), and customary limits of the integral are $\lambda \in [380,780]$ .
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The values of *X*, *Y*, and *Z* are bounded if the radiance spectrum *L*e,Ω,λ is bounded.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The reflective and transmissive cases are very similar to the emissive case, with a few differences.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The spectral radiance *L*e,Ω,λ is replaced by the spectral reflectance (or transmittance) *S(λ)* of the object being measured, multiplied by the spectral power distribution of the illuminant *I(λ)*.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] A few other XYZ-style color-matching functions have been available, correcting for known issues in the original 1931 color space.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] These functions imply their own XYZ-like and xyY-like color spaces.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] An alternative to the original 2° standard observer was defined in 1964, focusing on larger 10° stimuli.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] It was derived from the work of Stiles and Burch, and Speranskaya.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] For the 10° experiments, the observers were instructed to ignore the central 2° spot.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The 1964 *supplementary standard observer* function is recommended when dealing with more than about a 4° field of view, but some prefer to use it always as "human wide field color discrimination is about 2 to 3 times more accurate than foveal color discrimination".
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The color matching functions for both standard observers are published by the CIE, who also publishes the data openly for the 2° and 10° standard observer functions.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The data are discretized at 1 nm wavelength intervals from 360 nm to 830 nm.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Table lookup can become impractical for some computational tasks.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] That is, *g*(*x*) resembles a bell curve with its peak at *x* = *μ*, a spread/standard deviation of $1/\tau _{1}$ to the left of the mean, and spread of $1/\tau _{2}$ to the right of the mean.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The squared differences between the above approximation and the measured CIE XYZ color matching functions is less than the within-observer variance encountered in the experimental measurements used to form the CIE standards.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] It is also possible to use fewer Gaussian functions, with one Gaussian for each "lobe".
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] CIE 1964 fits well with a one-lobe function.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] The CIE XYZ color matching functions are nonnegative, and lead to nonnegative XYZ coordinates for all real colors (that is, for nonnegative light spectra).
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Other observers, such as for the CIE RGB space or other RGB color spaces, are defined by other sets of three color-matching functions, not generally nonnegative, and lead to tristimulus values in those other spaces, which may include negative coordinates for some real colors.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] function on the blue end of the spectrum.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] corrections sought to correct for the issue without deviating from the original methodology.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] and analogously for the following) is the XYZ-style color space defined using the CIE 1964 10° observer CMFs.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] which unlike the Wright–Guild functions (and the subsequent Judd–Vos corrections) are "directly measured", freeing them from the reconstruction errors of the 1931 functions.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Stiles and Burch also published a set of 2° RGB color-matching functions; however, no XYZ space derived from them has been formally recognized by the CIE.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] This space is based on the Stockman & Sharpe (2000) physiological 10° observer.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] According to Konica Minolta, the older CIE 1931 CMF exhibits metamerism failure (failure to predict when colors appear the same) for wide color gamut displays containing narrowband emitters like OLED, whereas the 2015 XYZF CMF is not affected.
[src:color-management/cie-1931-color-space] Older Sony manuals recommend using the Judd–Vos correction by applying an offset to the white point depending on the display technology used.
[src:color-management/color-management] Color management is necessary because different devices have different color capabilities and characteristics.
[src:color-management/color-management] For example, a monitor may display colors differently than a printer can reproduce them.
[src:color-management/color-management] Without color management, the same image may appear differently on different devices, leading to inconsistencies and inaccuracies.
[src:color-management/color-management] To achieve color management, a color profile is created for each device involved in the color workflow.
[src:color-management/color-management] This profile describes the device's color capabilities and characteristics, such as its color gamut (range of colors it can display or reproduce) and color temperature.
[src:color-management/color-management] These profiles are then used to translate colors between devices, ensuring consistent and accurate color reproduction.
[src:color-management/color-management] Color management is particularly important in industries such as graphic design, photography, and printing, where accurate color representation is crucial.
[src:color-management/color-management] It helps to maintain color consistency throughout the entire workflow, from capturing an image to displaying or printing it.
[src:color-management/color-management] Parts of color management are implemented in the operating system (OS), helper libraries, the application, and devices.
[src:color-management/color-management] The type of color profile that is typically used is called an ICC profile.
[src:color-management/color-management] A cross-platform view of color management is the use of an ICC-compatible color management system.
[src:color-management/color-management] There are other approaches to color management besides using ICC profiles.
[src:color-management/color-management] This is partly due to history and partly because of other needs than the ICC standard covers.
[src:color-management/color-management] The film and broadcasting industries make use of some of the same concepts, but they frequently rely on more limited boutique solutions.
[src:color-management/color-management] The film industry, for instance, often uses 3D LUTs (lookup table) to represent a complete color transformation for a specific RGB encoding.
[src:color-management/color-management] At the consumer level, system wide color management is available in most of Apple's products (macOS, iOS, iPadOS, watchOS).
[src:color-management/color-management] Microsoft Windows lacks system wide color management and virtually all applications do not employ color management.
[src:color-management/color-management] Windows' media player API is not color space aware, and if applications want to color manage videos manually, they have to incur significant performance and power consumption penalties.
[src:color-management/color-management] Android supports system wide color management, but most devices ship with color management disabled.
[src:color-management/color-management] Each color profile describes these colors relative to a standardized set of reference colors (the "Profile Connection Space").
[src:color-management/color-management] Color-managed software then uses these standardized profiles to translate color from one device to another.
[src:color-management/color-management] This is usually performed by a color management module (CMM).
[src:color-management/color-management] To describe the behavior of various output devices, they must be compared (measured) in relation to a standard color space.
[src:color-management/color-management] Often a step called linearization is performed first, to undo the effect of gamma correction that was done to get the most out of limited 8-bit color paths.
[src:color-management/color-management] Instruments used for measuring device colors include colorimeters and spectrophotometers.
[src:color-management/color-management] As an intermediate result, the device gamut is described in the form of scattered measurement data.
[src:color-management/color-management] The transformation of the scattered measurement data into a more regular form, usable by the application, is called *profiling*.
[src:color-management/color-management] Profiling is a complex process involving mathematics, intense computation, judgment, testing, and iteration.
[src:color-management/color-management] After the profiling is finished, an idealized color description of the device is created.
[src:color-management/color-management] Calibration is like characterization, except that it can include the adjustment of the device, as opposed to just the measurement of the device.
[src:color-management/color-management] Color management is sometimes sidestepped by calibrating devices to a common standard color space such as sRGB; when such calibration is done well enough, no color translations are needed to get all devices to handle colors consistently.
[src:color-management/color-management] This avoidance of the complexity of color management was one of the goals in the development of sRGB.
[src:color-management/color-management] Image formats themselves (such as TIFF, JPEG, PNG, EPS, PDF, and SVG) may contain embedded color profiles but are not required to do so by the image format.
[src:color-management/color-management] The International Color Consortium standard was created to bring various developers and manufacturers together.
[src:color-management/color-management] The ICC standard permits the exchange of output device characteristics and color spaces in the form of metadata.
[src:color-management/color-management] This allows the embedding of color profiles into images as well as storing them in a database or a profile directory.
[src:color-management/color-management] Working spaces, such as sRGB, Adobe RGB or ProPhoto are color spaces that facilitate good results while editing.
[src:color-management/color-management] For instance, pixels with equal values of R,G,B should appear neutral.
[src:color-management/color-management] Using a large (gamut) working space will lead to posterization, while using a small working space will lead to clipping.
[src:color-management/color-management] This trade-off is a consideration for the critical image editor.
[src:color-management/color-management] Color transformation, or color space conversion, is the transformation of the representation of a color from one color space to another.
[src:color-management/color-management] This calculation is required whenever data is exchanged inside a color-managed chain and carried out by a Color Matching Module.
[src:color-management/color-management] Transforming profiled color information to different output devices is achieved by referencing the profile data into a standard color space.
[src:color-management/color-management] It makes it easier to convert colors from one device to a selected standard color space and from that to the colors of another device.
[src:color-management/color-management] By ensuring that the reference color space covers the many possible colors that humans can see, this concept allows one to exchange colors between many different color output devices.
[src:color-management/color-management] Color transformations can be represented by two profiles (source profile and target profile) or by a devicelink profile.
[src:color-management/color-management] In this process there are approximations involved which make sure that the image keeps its important color qualities and also gives an opportunity to control on how the colors are being changed.
[src:color-management/color-management] In the terminology of the International Color Consortium, a translation between two color spaces can go through a *profile connection space* (PCS): Color Space 1 → PCS (CIELAB or CIEXYZ) → Color space 2; conversions into and out of the PCS are each specified by a profile.
[src:color-management/color-management] In nearly every translation process, we have to deal with the fact that the color gamut of different devices vary in range which makes an accurate reproduction impossible.
[src:color-management/color-management] They therefore need some rearrangement near the borders of the gamut.
[src:color-management/color-management] Some colors must be shifted to the inside of the gamut, as they otherwise cannot be represented on the output device and would simply be clipped.
[src:color-management/color-management] This so-called gamut mismatch occurs for example, when we translate from the RGB color space with a wider gamut into the CMYK color space with a narrower gamut range.
[src:color-management/color-management] In this example, the dark highly saturated purplish-blue color of a typical computer monitor's "blue" primary is impossible to print on paper with a typical CMYK printer.
[src:color-management/color-management] The nearest approximation within the printer's gamut will be much less saturated.
[src:color-management/color-management] Conversely, an inkjet printer's "cyan" primary, a saturated mid-brightness blue, is outside the gamut of a typical computer monitor.
[src:color-management/color-management] The color management system can utilize various methods to achieve desired results and give experienced users control of the gamut mapping behavior.
[src:color-management/color-management] When the gamut of source color space exceeds that of the destination, saturated colors are liable to become clipped (inaccurately represented), or more formally burned.
[src:color-management/color-management] The color management module can deal with this problem in several ways.
[src:color-management/color-management] The ICC specification includes four different rendering intents, listed below.
[src:color-management/color-management] Before the actual rendering intent is carried out, one can temporarily simulate the rendering by soft proofing.
[src:color-management/color-management] Absolute colorimetry and relative colorimetry actually use the same table but differ in the adjustment for the white point media.
[src:color-management/color-management] If the output device has a much larger gamut than the source profile, i.e., all the colors in the source can be represented in the output, using the absolute colorimetry rendering intent would ideally (ignoring noise, precision, etc.) give an exact output of the specified CIELAB values.
[src:color-management/color-management] Perceptually, the colors may appear incorrect, but instrument measurements of the resulting output would match the source.
[src:color-management/color-management] Colors outside of the proof print system's possible color are mapped to the boundary of the color gamut.
[src:color-management/color-management] Absolute colorimetry is useful to get an exact specified color (e.g., IBM blue), or to quantify the accuracy of mapping methods.
[src:color-management/color-management] The goal in relative colorimetry is to be truthful to the specified color, with only a correction for the media.
[src:color-management/color-management] Relative colorimetry is useful in proofing applications, since it can be used to get an idea of how a print on one device will appear on a different device.
[src:color-management/color-management] Media differences are the only thing that one really should adjust for, although some gamut mapping also needs to be applied.
[src:color-management/color-management] Usually this is done in a way where hue and lightness are maintained at the cost of reduced saturation.
[src:color-management/color-management] By default, in-gamut colors are unchanged, while out-of-gamut colors are clamped.
[src:color-management/color-management] Relative colorimetric is the default rendering intent on many systems.
[src:color-management/color-management] The perceptual intent smoothly moves out-of-gamut colors into gamut, preserving gradations, but distorts in-gamut colors in the process.
[src:color-management/color-management] Like the saturation intent, the results really depend upon the profile maker.
[src:color-management/color-management] This is even how some of the competitors in this market differentiate themselves.
[src:color-management/color-management] The profile maker tries to make results pleasing on this intent.
[src:color-management/color-management] Perceptual rendering is recommended for color separation.
[src:color-management/color-management] The saturation intent is designed to present eye-catching business graphics by preserving the saturation (colorfulness).
[src:color-management/color-management] It is most useful in charts and diagrams, where there is a discrete palette of colors that the designer wants saturated to make them intense, but where specific hue is less important.
[src:color-management/color-management] In practice, photographers almost always use relative or perceptual intent, as for natural images, absolute causes color cast, while saturation produces unnatural colors.
[src:color-management/color-management] If an entire image is in-gamut, relative is perfect, but when there are out of gamut colors, which is preferable depends on a case-by-case basis.
[src:color-management/color-management] CMMs may offer options for BPC and partial chromatic adaptation.
[src:color-management/color-management] A black point correction (BPC) is not applied for absolute colorimetric or devicelink profiles.
[src:color-management/color-management] For ICCv4, it is always applied to the perceptual intent.
[src:color-management/color-management] ICCv2 sRGB profiles differ among each other in a number of ways, one of which being whether BPC is applied.
[src:color-management/color-management] Some well known CMMs are ColorSync, Adobe CMM, Little CMS, and ArgyllCMS.
[src:color-management/color-management] System wide color management is used in iOS, iPadOS and watchOS as well.
[src:color-management/color-management] Microsoft Windows prior to Windows 10 recommends the sRGB color space.
[src:color-management/color-management] Since Windows 10 with High Dynamic Range (HDR) enabled and since Windows 11 with Auto Color Management (ACM) enabled, it recommends the DCI-P3 color space.
[src:color-management/color-management] Since 1997 color management in Windows is available through an ICC color management system: ICM (Image Color Management).
[src:color-management/color-management] Beginning with Windows Vista, Microsoft introduced a new color architecture known as WCS (Windows Color System).
[src:color-management/color-management] WCS supplements the ICM system in Windows 2000 and Windows XP, originally written by Heidelberg.
[src:color-management/color-management] Apps need to be aware of color management and tag the content appropriately to accurately display colors.
[src:color-management/color-management] Otherwise, (unlike macOS) Windows will display the colors to the maximum extent of the display's gamut, resulting in over-saturated colors on wide-gamut displays.
[src:color-management/color-management] To fix this issue, Microsoft includes a new feature called "Auto Color Management" since Windows 11 2022.
[src:color-management/color-management] A few exception is the ICM profile includes the Video Card Gamma Table (VCGT) data, and the VCGT data will be applied globally.
[src:color-management/color-management] Windows Photo Viewer from Windows 7 (also included in later Windows versions) performs proper color management, however, the newer Windows Photos app in Windows 8, 10, 11 does not perform legacy color management (ICM/WCS) until version v2022.31070.26005.0.
[src:color-management/color-management] Other Windows components, including Microsoft Paint, Snipping Tool, Windows Desktop, Windows Explorer, do not perform legacy color management.
[src:color-management/color-management] In Windows 8, the DXVA API and the WIC API added support for color space conversion, but in Windows 8 it's still not support wide color gamut.
[src:color-management/color-management] Unfortunately, the vast majority of personal applications do not use the Windows Color System.
[src:color-management/color-management] For applications that do employ color management (typically web browsers), color management tend to apply for only images and UI, but not videos.
[src:color-management/color-management] This is because Windows' media player API is not color space aware.
[src:color-management/color-management] Thus, browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge) are only able to do color management for images but not video.
[src:color-management/color-management] For the same reason, virtually no video players on Windows support color management (including the default Windows Movies & TV app and VLC Media Player), with Media Player Classic Home Cinema being a rare exception.
[src:color-management/color-management] Windows 10 1607 supports High Dynamic Range (HDR).
[src:color-management/color-management] Windows 11 22H2 supports Auto Color Management (ACM) which further optimized for OLED and/or wide-color gamut monitors.
[src:color-management/color-management] Applications can be updated to support ACM and wide-color gamut; Microsoft Edge, Google Chrome, Windows Photos and Windows Media Player 2022 are known to support ACM.
[src:color-management/color-management] While ACM can do color space conversion, but actual color management factors (such as color temperature and contrast) are also depend on OSD settings of monitor or TV set, and/or depend on software/driver settings of GPU/monitor.
[src:color-management/color-management] On Android, system wide color management is introduced in Android Oreo 8.1.
[src:color-management/color-management] However, most Android phones are shipped with color management disabled (ex: 'adaptive' color profile on Google Pixel, 'vivid' color profile on Samsung Galaxy).
[src:color-management/color-management] This oversaturates sRGB content to the native display gamut, typically DCI-P3.
[src:color-management/color-management] Users need to manually select the 'natural' color profile to enable color management, enabling accurate display of sRGB and P3 wide color content.
[src:color-management/color-management] Operating systems that use the X Window System for graphics can use ICC profiles, and support for color management on Linux, still less mature than on other platforms, is coordinated through OpenICC at freedesktop.org and makes use of LittleCMS.
[src:color-management/color-management] Certain image filetypes (TIFF and Photoshop) include the notion of color channels for specifying the *color mode* of the file.
[src:color-management/color-management] The most commonly used channels are RGB (mainly for display (monitors) but also for some desktop printing) and CMYK (for commercial printing).
[src:color-management/color-management] An additional *alpha* channel may specify a transparency mask value.
[src:color-management/color-management] Some image software (such as Photoshop) perform automatic color separation to maintain color information in CMYK mode using a specified ICC profile such as **US Web Coated (SWOP) v2**.
[src:color-management/color-management] Adobe software includes its own color management engine - Adobe Color Engine.
[src:color-management/color-management] It is also available as a separate Color Management Module - Adobe CMM for use by non-Adobe applications that supports 3rd-party CMMs.
[src:color-management/color-management] As of 2005, most web browsers ignored color profiles.
[src:color-management/color-management] Notable exceptions were Safari, starting with version 2.0, and Firefox starting with version 3.
[src:color-management/color-management] Although disabled by default in Firefox 3.0, ICC v2 and ICC v4 color management could be enabled by using an add-on or setting a configuration option.
[src:color-management/color-management] As of July 2019, Safari, Chrome and Firefox fully support color management.
[src:color-management/color-management] Most browsers only do color management for images and CSS elements, but not video.
[src:color-management/color-management] Regarding mobile browsers, Safari 13.1 (on iOS 13.4.1) recognizes the device color profile and can displays images accordingly.
[src:color-management/color-management] Chrome 83 (on Android 9) ignores the display profile, simply converting all images to sRGB.
[src:color-management/color-management] As of 2023, Chrome 114, Android Browser 114 and Firefox for Android 115 support multiple colorspaces.
[src:color-management/color-management] The same is valid for their desktop counterparts: Chrome 118, Edge 114, Safari 16.6, Firefox 117 and Opera 100.
[src:color-management/color-model] In color science, a **color model** is an abstract mathematical model describing the way colors can be represented as tuples of numbers, typically as three or four values or color components.
[src:color-management/color-model] It differs from a color space in that a color model is not absolute, that is, there is no way to map a color within a color model to a point in a color space.
[src:color-management/color-model] This article describes ways in which human color vision can be modeled, and discusses some of the models in common use.
[src:color-management/color-model] One can picture this space as a region in three-dimensional Euclidean space if one identifies the *x*, *y*, and *z* axes with the stimuli for the long-wavelength (*L*), medium-wavelength (*M*), and short-wavelength (*S*) light receptors.
[src:color-management/color-model] White has no definite position in this diagram; rather it is defined according to the color temperature or white balance as desired or as available from ambient lighting.
[src:color-management/color-model] The most saturated colors are located at the outer rim of the region, with brighter colors farther removed from the origin.
[src:color-management/color-model] Colors like brown or grey are perceived when, respectively, orange light and white light are received, but at a lower intensity than what it would be expected for the colors orange and white given the surrounding illumination.
[src:color-management/color-model] One can observe this phenomenon by watching the screen of an overhead projector during a meeting: one sees black lettering on a white background, even though the "black" has in fact not become darker than the white screen on which it is projected before the projector was turned on.
[src:color-management/color-model] The "black" areas have not actually become darker but appear "black" relative to the higher intensity "white" projected onto the screen around it.
[src:color-management/color-model] The human tristimulus space has the property that additive mixing of colors corresponds to the adding of vectors in this space.
[src:color-management/color-model] This makes it easy to, for example, describe the possible colors (gamut) that can be constructed from the red, green, and blue primaries in a computer display.
[src:color-management/color-model] Media that transmit light (such as television) use additive color mixing with primary colors of red, green, and blue, each of which stimulates one of the three types of the eye's color receptors with as little stimulation as possible of the other two.
[src:color-management/color-model] Mixtures of light of these primary colors cover a large part of the human color space and thus produce a large part of human color experiences.
[src:color-management/color-model] This is why color television sets or color computer monitors need only produce mixtures of red, green and blue light.
[src:color-management/color-model] Other primary colors could in principle be used, but with red, green and blue the largest portion of the human color space can be captured.
[src:color-management/color-model] Unfortunately there is no exact consensus as to what loci in the chromaticity diagram the red, green, and blue colors should have, so the same RGB values can give rise to slightly different colors on different screens.
[src:color-management/color-model] Thus an RGB value does not define the same *color* across devices without some kind of color management.
[src:color-management/color-model] It is possible to achieve a large range of colors seen by humans by combining cyan, magenta, and yellow transparent dyes/inks on a white substrate.
[src:color-management/color-model] These are the *subtractive* primary colors.
[src:color-management/color-model] Often a fourth ink, black, is added to improve reproduction of some dark colors.
[src:color-management/color-model] This is called the "CMY" or "CMYK" color space.
[src:color-management/color-model] The cyan ink absorbs red light but transmits green and blue, the magenta ink absorbs green light but transmits red and blue, and the yellow ink absorbs blue light but transmits red and green.
[src:color-management/color-model] The white substrate reflects the transmitted light back to the viewer.
[src:color-management/color-model] Because in practice the CMY inks suitable for printing also reflect a little bit of color, making a deep and neutral black impossible, the K (black ink) component, usually printed last, is needed to compensate for their deficiencies.
[src:color-management/color-model] Use of a separate black ink is also economically driven when a lot of black content is expected, e.g. in text media, to reduce simultaneous use of the three colored inks.
[src:color-management/color-model] The dyes used in traditional color photographic prints and slides are much more perfectly transparent, so a K component is normally not needed or used in those media.
[src:color-management/color-model] A number of color models exist in which colors are fit into conic, cylindrical or spherical shapes, with neutrals running from black to white along a central axis, and hues corresponding to angles around the perimeter.
[src:color-management/color-model] Arrangements of this type date back to the 18th century, and continue to be developed in the most modern and scientific models.
[src:color-management/color-model] Different color theorists have each designed unique color solids.
[src:color-management/color-model] Many are in the shape of a sphere, whereas others are warped three-dimensional ellipsoid figures—these variations being designed to express some aspect of the relationship of the colors more clearly.
[src:color-management/color-model] The color spheres conceived by Phillip Otto Runge and Johannes Itten are typical examples and prototypes for many other color solid schematics.
[src:color-management/color-model] The models of Runge and Itten are basically identical, and form the basis for the description below.
[src:color-management/color-model] Pure, saturated hues of equal brightness are located around the equator at the periphery of the color sphere.
[src:color-management/color-model] As in the color wheel, contrasting (or complementary) hues are located opposite each other.
[src:color-management/color-model] Moving toward the center of the color sphere on the equatorial plane, colors become less and less saturated, until all colors meet at the central axis as a neutral gray.
[src:color-management/color-model] Moving vertically in the color sphere, colors become lighter (toward the top) and darker (toward the bottom).
[src:color-management/color-model] At the upper pole, all hues meet in white; at the bottom pole, all hues meet in black.
[src:color-management/color-model] The vertical axis of the color sphere, then, is gray all along its length, varying from black at the bottom to white at the top.
[src:color-management/color-model] All pure (saturated) hues are located on the surface of the sphere, varying from light to dark down the color sphere.
[src:color-management/color-model] All impure (unsaturated hues, created by mixing contrasting colors) comprise the sphere's interior, likewise varying in brightness from top to bottom.
[src:color-management/color-model] Painters long mixed colors by combining relatively bright pigments with black and white.
[src:color-management/color-model] The RGB gamut can be arranged in a cube.
[src:color-management/color-model] The RGB model is not very intuitive to artists used to using traditional models based on tints, shades and tones.
[src:color-management/color-model] The HSL and HSV color models were designed to fix this.
[src:color-management/color-model] HSL and HSV are both cylindrical geometries, with hue, their angular dimension, starting at the red primary at 0°, passing through the green primary at 120° and the blue primary at 240°, and then wrapping back to red at 360°.
[src:color-management/color-model] In each geometry, the central vertical axis comprises the *neutral*, *achromatic*, or *gray* colors, ranging from black at lightness 0 or value 0, the bottom, to white at lightness 1 or value 1, the top.
[src:color-management/color-model] Most televisions, computer displays, and projectors produce colors by combining red, green, and blue light in varying intensities—the RGB additive primary colors.
[src:color-management/color-model] However, the relationship between the constituent amounts of red, green, and blue light and the resulting color is unintuitive, especially for inexperienced users, and for users familiar with subtractive color mixing of paints or traditional artists’ models based on tints and shades.
[src:color-management/color-model] In an attempt to accommodate more traditional and intuitive color mixing models, computer graphics pioneers at PARC and NYIT developed the HSV model in the mid-1970s, formally described by Alvy Ray Smith in the August 1978 issue of *Computer Graphics*.
[src:color-management/color-model] In the same issue, Joblove and Greenberg described the HSL model—whose dimensions they labeled *hue*, *relative chroma*, and *intensity*—and compared it to HSV.
[src:color-management/color-model] The following year, 1979, at SIGGRAPH, Tektronix introduced graphics terminals using HSL for color designation, and the Computer Graphics Standards Committee recommended it in their annual status report.
[src:color-management/color-model] These models were useful not only because they were more intuitive than raw RGB values, but also because the conversions to and from RGB were extremely fast to compute: they could run in real time on the hardware of the 1970s.
[src:color-management/color-model] Consequently, these models and similar ones have become ubiquitous throughout image editing and graphics software since then.
[src:color-management/color-model] Later, Munsell discovered that if hue, value, and chroma were to be kept perceptually uniform, achievable surface colors could not be forced into a regular shape.
[src:color-management/color-model] Three-dimensional representation of the 1943 Munsell renotations.
[src:color-management/color-model] Notice the irregularity of the shape when compared to Munsell's earlier color sphere, at left.
[src:color-management/color-model] Another influential older cylindrical color model is the early-20th-century Munsell color system.
[src:color-management/color-model] In the 1940s, the Optical Society of America made extensive measurements, and adjusted the arrangement of Munsell colors, issuing a set of "renotations".
[src:color-management/color-model] The trouble with the Munsell system for computer graphics applications is that its colors are not specified via any set of simple equations, but only via its foundational measurements: effectively a lookup table.
[src:color-management/color-model] Converting from RGB ↔ Munsell requires interpolating between that table's entries, and is extremely computationally expensive in comparison with converting from RGB ↔ HSL or RGB ↔ HSV which only requires a few simple arithmetic operations.
[src:color-management/color-model] The Swedish Natural Color System (NCS), widely used in Europe, takes a similar approach to the Ostwald bicone at right.
[src:color-management/color-model] In densitometry, a model quite similar to the hue defined above is used for describing colors of CMYK process inks.
[src:color-management/color-model] In 1953, Frank Preucil developed two geometric arrangements of hue, the "Preucil hue circle" and the "Preucil hue hexagon", analogous to our *H* and *H*2, respectively, but defined relative to idealized cyan, yellow, and magenta ink colors.
[src:color-management/color-model] The "Preucil *hue error*" of an ink indicates the difference in the "hue circle" between its color and the hue of the corresponding idealized ink color.
[src:color-management/color-model] The *grayness* of an ink is *m*/*M*, where *m* and *M* are the minimum and maximum among the amounts of idealized cyan, magenta, and yellow in a density measurement.
[src:color-management/color-model] The CIE's most recent model, CIECAM02 (CAM stands for "color appearance model"), is more theoretically sophisticated and computationally complex than earlier models.
[src:color-management/color-model] Its aims are to fix several of the problems with models such as CIELAB and CIELUV, and to explain not only responses in carefully controlled experimental environments, but also to model the color appearance of real-world scenes.
[src:color-management/color-model] Its dimensions *J* (lightness), *C* (chroma), and *h* (hue) define a polar-coordinate geometry.
[src:color-management/color-model] There are various types of color systems that classify color and analyze their effects.
[src:color-management/color-model] The American Munsell color system devised by Albert H.
[src:color-management/color-model] Munsell is a famous classification that organizes various colors into a color solid based on hue, saturation and value.
[src:color-management/color-model] Other important color systems include the Swedish Natural Color System (NCS), the Optical Society of America's Uniform Color Space (OSA-UCS), and the Hungarian Coloroid system developed by Antal Nemcsics from the Budapest University of Technology and Economics.
[src:color-management/color-model] Of those, the NCS is based on the opponent-process color model, while the Munsell, the OSA-UCS and the Coloroid attempt to model color uniformity.
[src:color-management/color-model] The American Pantone and the German RAL commercial color-matching systems differ from the previous ones in that their color spaces are not based on an underlying color model.
[src:color-management/color-model] The Icelandic Spot Matching System (SMS) is a so-called media neutral color palette where all the colors can be reproduced online, on Television and in standard process printing (CMYK or better).
[src:color-management/color-model] We also use "color model" to indicate a model or mechanism of color vision for explaining how color signals are processed from visual cones to ganglion cells.
[src:color-management/color-model] For simplicity, we call these models color mechanism models.
[src:color-management/color-model] The classical color mechanism models are Young–Helmholtz's trichromatic model and Hering's opponent-process model.
[src:color-management/color-model] Though these two theories were initially thought to be at odds, it later came to be hypothesized that the mechanisms responsible for color opponency receive signals from the three types of cones and process them at a more complex level.
[src:color-management/color-model] A widely accepted model is called the zone model.
[src:color-management/gamut] In color reproduction and colorimetry, a **gamut**, or **color gamut** /ˈɡæmət/, is a convex set containing the colors that can be accurately represented, i.e. reproduced by an output device (e.g. printer or display) or measured by an input device (e.g. camera or visual system).
[src:color-management/gamut] Devices with a larger gamut can represent more colors.
[src:color-management/gamut] Similarly, gamut may also refer to the colors within a defined color space, which is not linked to a specific device.
[src:color-management/gamut] A trichromatic gamut is often visualized as a color triangle.
[src:color-management/gamut] A less common usage defines gamut as the subset of colors contained within an image, scene or video.
[src:color-management/gamut] The term *gamut* was adopted from the field of music, where the medieval Latin expression "gamma ut" meant the lowest tone of the G scale and, in time, came to imply the entire range of musical notes of which musical melodies are composed.
[src:color-management/gamut] Shakespeare's use of the term in *The Taming of the Shrew* is sometimes attributed to the author / musician Thomas Morley.
[src:color-management/gamut] The gamut of a device or process is that portion of the color space that can be represented, or reproduced.
[src:color-management/gamut] Generally, the color gamut is specified in the hue–saturation plane, as a system can usually produce colors over a wide intensity range within its color gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] Device gamuts must use real primaries (those that can be represented by a physical spectral power distribution) and therefore are always *incomplete* (smaller than the human visible gamut).
[src:color-management/gamut] No gamut defined by a finite number of primaries can represent the entire human visible gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] Three primaries are necessary for representing an approximation of the human visible gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] More primaries can be used to increase the size of the gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] For example, while painting with red, yellow and blue pigments is sufficient for modeling color vision, adding further pigments (e.g. orange or green) can increase the size of the gamut, allowing the reproduction of more saturated colors.
[src:color-management/gamut] While processing a digital image, the most convenient color model used is the RGB model.
[src:color-management/gamut] Printing the image requires transforming the image from the original RGB color model to the printer's CMYK color model.
[src:color-management/gamut] During this process, the colors from the RGB model which are out of gamut must be somehow converted to approximate values within the CMYK model.
[src:color-management/gamut] Simply trimming only the colors which are out of gamut to the closest colors in the destination space would burn the image.
[src:color-management/gamut] There are several algorithms approximating this transformation, but none of them can be truly perfect, since those colors are simply out of the target device's capabilities.
[src:color-management/gamut] This is why identifying the colors in an image that are out of gamut in the target color space as soon as possible during processing is critical for the quality of the final product.
[src:color-management/gamut] It is also important to remember that there are colors inside the CMYK gamut that are outside the most commonly used RGB color spaces, such as sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:color-management/gamut] Color management is the process of ensuring consistent and accurate colors across devices with different gamuts.
[src:color-management/gamut] Color management handles the transformations between color gamuts and canonical color spaces to ensure that colors are represented equally on different devices.
[src:color-management/gamut] A device's gamut is defined by a color profile, usually the ICC profile, which relates the gamut to a standardized color space and allows for calibration of the device.
[src:color-management/gamut] Transforming from one gamut to a smaller gamut loses information as *out-of-gamut* colors are projected on to the smaller gamut and transforming back to the larger gamut does not regain this lost information.
[src:color-management/gamut] Colorimetry is the measurement of color, generally in a way that mimics human color perception.
[src:color-management/gamut] Input devices such as digital cameras or scanners are made to mimic trichromatic human color perception and are based on three sensors elements with different spectral sensitivities, ideally aligned approximately with the spectral sensitivities of human photopsins.
[src:color-management/gamut] In this sense, they have a similar gamut to the human visual system.
[src:color-management/gamut] However, most of these devices violate the Luther condition and are not intended to be truly colorimetric, with the exception of tristimulus colorimeters.
[src:color-management/gamut] Higher-dimension input devices, such as multispectral imagers, hyperspectral imagers or spectrometers, capture color at a much larger gamut, dimensionally, than the human visible gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] To be perceived by humans, the images must first be down-dimensionalized and treated with false color.
[src:color-management/gamut] The extent of color that can be detected by the average human, approximated by the standard observer, is the *visible (or visual) gamut*.
[src:color-management/gamut] The chromaticities present in the visible gamut are usually visualized in the CIE 1931 chromaticity diagram, where the spectral locus (curved edge) represents the monochromatic (single-wavelength) or spectral colors.
[src:color-management/gamut] As current displays have a smaller gamut than the visible gamut, the colors that are out-of-gamut are reproduced as colors inside the display's gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] Device gamuts are generally depicted in reference to the visible gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] The standard observer represents a typical human, but colorblindness leads to a reduced visible gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] Optimal colors are the most chromatic colors that surfaces can have*.
[src:color-management/gamut] The color solid bounded by the set of all optimal colors is called the optimal color solid or Rösch–MacAdam color solid.
[src:color-management/gamut] For now, we are unable to produce objects with such colors, at least not without recurring to more complex physical phenomena.
[src:color-management/gamut] The reflectance spectrum of a color is the amount of light of each wavelength that it reflects, in proportion to a given maximum, which has the value of 1 (100%).
[src:color-management/gamut] If the reflectance spectrum of a color is 0 (0%) or 1 (100%) across the entire visible spectrum, and it has no more than two transitions between 0 and 1, or 1 and 0, then it is an optimal color.
[src:color-management/gamut] With the current state of technology, we are unable to produce any material or pigment with these properties.
[src:color-management/gamut] The first type produces colors that are similar to the spectral colors and follow roughly the horseshoe-shaped portion of the CIE xy chromaticity diagram (the spectral locus), but are, in surfaces, more chromatic, although less spectrally pure.
[src:color-management/gamut] The second type produces colors that are similar to (but, in surfaces, more chromatic and less spectrally pure than) the colors on the straight line in the CIE xy chromaticity diagram (the line of purples), leading to magenta or purple-like colors.
[src:color-management/gamut] In short: In optimal color solids, spectral colors are equivalent to black (0 lightness, 0 chroma), but have full spectral purity (they are located in the horseshoe-shaped spectral locus of the chromaticiy diagram).
[src:color-management/gamut] This means that, in linear color spaces, the optimal color solid is centrally symmetric.
[src:color-management/gamut] This is due to the following: If the portion of the reflectance spectrum of a color is spectral red (which is located at one end of the spectrum), it will be seen as black.
[src:color-management/gamut] If the size of the portion of total or reflectance is increased, now covering from the red end of the spectrum to the yellow wavelengths, it will be seen as red.
[src:color-management/gamut] If the portion is expanded even more, covering the green wavelengths, it will be seen as orange or yellow.
[src:color-management/gamut] If it is expanded even more, it will cover more wavelengths than the yellow semichrome does, approaching white, until it is reached when the full spectrum is reflected.
[src:color-management/gamut] The described process is called "cumulation".
[src:color-management/gamut] Cumulation can be started at either end of the visible spectrum (we just described cumulation starting from the red end of the spectrum, generating the "warm" sharp edge), cumulation starting at the violet end of the spectrum will generate the "cool" sharp edge.
[src:color-management/gamut] Each hue has a maximum chroma point, semichrome, or full color; objects cannot have a color of that hue with a higher chroma.
[src:color-management/gamut] They are the most chromatic, vibrant colors that objects can have.
[src:color-management/gamut] They were called **semichromes** or **full colors** by the German chemist and philosopher Wilhelm Ostwald in the early 20th century.
[src:color-management/gamut] If B is the complementary wavelength of wavelength A, then the straight line that connects A and B passes through the achromatic axis in a linear color space, such as LMS or CIE 1931 XYZ.
[src:color-management/gamut] If the reflectance spectrum of a color is 1 (100%) for all the wavelengths between A and B, and 0 for all the wavelengths of the other half of the color space, then that color is a maximum chroma color, semichrome, or full color (this is the explanation to why they were called **semi**chromes).
[src:color-management/gamut] Thus, maximum chroma colors are a type of optimal color.
[src:color-management/gamut] As explained, full colors are far from being monochromatic.
[src:color-management/gamut] If the spectral purity of a maximum chroma color is increased, its chroma decreases, because it will approach the visible spectrum, ergo, it will approach black.
[src:color-management/gamut] In perceptually uniform color spaces, the lightness of the full colors varies from around 30% in the violetish blue hues, to around 90% in the yellowish hues.
[src:color-management/gamut] The chroma of each maximum chroma point also varies depending on the hue; in optimal color solids plotted in perceptually uniform color spaces, semichromes like red, green, blue, violet, and magenta have a high chroma, while semichromes like yellow, orange, and cyan have a slightly lower chroma.
[src:color-management/gamut] In the beginning of the 20th century, industrial demands for a controllable way to describe colors and the new possibility to measure light spectra initiated intense research on mathematical descriptions of colors.
[src:color-management/gamut] The idea of optimal colors was introduced by the Baltic German chemist Wilhelm Ostwald.
[src:color-management/gamut] Schrödinger's work was further developed by David MacAdam and Siegfried Rösch.
[src:color-management/gamut] MacAdam was the first person to calculate precise coordinates of selected points on the boundary of the optimal color solid in the CIE 1931 color space for lightness levels from Y = 10 to 95 in steps of 10 units.
[src:color-management/gamut] This enabled him to draw the optimal color solid at an acceptable degree of precision.
[src:color-management/gamut] Because of his achievement, the boundary of the optimal color solid is called the *MacAdam limit* (1935).
[src:color-management/gamut] On modern computers, it is possible to calculate an optimal color solid with great precision in seconds.
[src:color-management/gamut] Usually, only the MacAdam limits (the optimal colors, the boundary of the optimal color solid) are computed, because all the other (non-optimal) possible surface colors exist inside the boundary.
[src:color-management/gamut] The optimal color solid represents the **theoretical** limit of the possible colors of surfaces.
[src:color-management/gamut] However, in real life, objects are not color-optimal (at least not the ones that present ordinary reflection).
[src:color-management/gamut] This means that, in practice, the color of a surface is always less chromatic than the optimal color of the same hue and lightness.
[src:color-management/gamut] For practical applications, a smaller, more realistic gamut may be needed.
[src:color-management/gamut] Pointer published a gamut for real surfaces with diffuse reflection using 4089 samples, (surfaces with specular reflection, "glossy", can fall outside of this gamut).
[src:color-management/gamut] Originally called a "Munsell Color Cascade", the limits are more commonly called *Pointer's Gamut* after his work.
[src:color-management/gamut] In subtractive color systems, the color gamut is more often an irregular, rounded region.
[src:color-management/gamut] The gamut of a CMYK color space is, ideally, the same as that for an RGB one.
[src:color-management/gamut] In practice, due to the way raster-printed colors interact with each other and the paper and due to their non-ideal absorption spectra, the gamut has rounded corners.
[src:color-management/gamut] Light sources used as primaries in an additive color reproduction system need to be bright, so they are generally not close to monochromatic.
[src:color-management/gamut] That is, the color gamut of most variable-color light sources can be understood as a result of difficulties producing pure monochromatic (single wavelength) light.
[src:color-management/gamut] The best technological source of monochromatic light is the laser, which can be rather expensive and impractical for many systems.
[src:color-management/gamut] Systems that use additive color processes usually have a color gamut which is roughly a convex polygon (or a slightly concave shape) in a perceptually uniform hue-chroma plane (not to be confused with the chromaticity diagram).
[src:color-management/gamut] The vertices of the polygon are the most chromatic colors that the system can produce.
[src:color-management/gamut] The Ultra HD Forum defines a wide-color gamut (WCG) as a color gamut wider than Rec.
[src:color-management/gamut] The print gamut achieved by using cyan, magenta, yellow, and black inks is sometimes a limitation, for example when printing colors of corporate logos.
[src:color-management/gamut] Therefore, some methods of color printing use additional ink colors to achieve a larger gamut.
[src:color-management/gamut] For example, some use green, orange, and violet inks to increase the achievable saturation of hues near those.
[src:color-management/gamut] These method are variously called heptatone color printing, extended gamut printing, and 7-color printing, etc.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] In color management, an **ICC profile** is a set of data that characterizes a color input or output device, or a color space, according to standards promulgated by the International Color Consortium (ICC).
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Profiles describe the color attributes of a particular device or viewing requirement by defining a mapping between the device source or target color space and a *profile connection space* (PCS).
[src:color-management/icc-profile] This PCS is either CIELAB (L*a*b*) or CIEXYZ.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Mappings may be specified using tables, to which interpolation is applied, or through a series of parameters for transformations.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Every device that captures or displays color can be profiled.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Some manufacturers provide profiles for their products, and there are several products that allow an end-user to generate their own color profiles, typically through the use of a tristimulus colorimeter or a spectrophotometer (sometimes called a spectrocolorimeter).
[src:color-management/icc-profile] The ICC defines the format precisely but does not define algorithms or processing details.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] This means there is room for variation between different applications and systems that work with ICC profiles.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Two main generations are used: the legacy ICCv2 and the December 2001 ICCv4.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] The current version of the format specification (ICC.1) is 4.4.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] ICC has also published a preliminary specification for iccMAX (ICC.2) or ICCv5, a next-generation color management architecture with significantly expanded functionality and a choice of colorimetric, spectral or material connection space.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] To see how this works in practice, suppose we have a particular RGB and CMYK color space, and want to convert from this RGB to that CMYK.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] The first step is to obtain the two ICC profiles concerned.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] To perform the conversion, each RGB triplet is first converted to the Profile connection space (PCS) using the RGB profile.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] If necessary the PCS is converted between CIELAB and CIEXYZ, a well defined transformation.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Then the PCS is converted to the four values of C, M, Y, K required using the second profile.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] So a profile is essentially a pair of mappings; one from a color space to the PCS and a second from the PCS to the color space.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] A mapping might be implemented using tables of color values to be interpolated or be implemented using a series of mathematical formulae.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] A profile might define several mappings, according to rendering intent.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] These mappings allow a choice between closest possible color matching, and remapping the entire color range to allow for different gamuts.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] The reference illuminant of the Profile connection space (PCS) is a 16-bit fractional approximation of D50; its white point is XYZ=(0.9642, 1.000, 0.8249).
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Different source/destination white points are adapted using the Bradford transformation.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Another kind of profile is the device link profile.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] Instead of mapping between a device color space and a PCS, it maps between two specific device spaces.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] While this is less flexible, it allows for a more accurate or purposeful conversion of color between devices.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] For example, a conversion between two CMYK devices could ensure that colors using only black ink convert to target colors using only black ink.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] The ICC profile specification, currently being progressed as International Standard ISO 15076-1:2005, is widely referred to in other standards.
[src:color-management/icc-profile] The following International and *de facto* standards are known to make reference to ICC profiles.
